\begin_layout Standard
If the quantity produced by each player 
\begin_inset Formula $i$
\end_inset

 is 
\begin_inset Formula $q_{i}$
\end_inset

 and the price function is 
\begin_inset Formula $p$
\end_inset

, the utility of each player is given by:
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
u_{i}(q_{1},\ldots,q_{n})=q_{i}\cdot p\left(\sum_{j=1}^{n}q_{j}\right)
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
assuming
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
p\left(\sum_{j=1}^{n}q_{j}\right)=1-\sum_{j=1}^{n}q_{j}
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The problem is finding the maximum point 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
max_{q_{i}\geq0}q_{i}\left(1-\sum_{j=1}^{n}q_{j}\right)
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Taking a derivative, the first-order condition is:
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
1-\sum_{j=1,j\neq i}^{n}q_{j}-2q_{i}=0\Rightarrow q_{i}=\frac{1-\sum_{j=1,j\neq i}^{n}q_{j}}{2}
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Considering the solution must be identical for every 
\begin_inset Formula $q_{i}$
\end_inset

, the only possibility is having
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
q_{i}=\frac{1-(n-1)q_{i}}{2}\Rightarrow q_{i}=\frac{1}{n+1}
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

